<div class="comment-wrapper"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment"><div class="avatar"><img src="https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d53b7c5f9b5f5557b9082face9b632a0?s=50"></div><header><strong>[Discussion] Design guideline rule for `:`</strong> from <string>Dave Abrahams</string> &lt;dabrahams at apple.com&gt;<p>June 22, 2016 at 10:00:00am</p></header><div class="content"><p>on Wed Jun 22 2016, Adrian Zubarev &lt;swift-evolution at swift.org&gt; wrote:<br></p><p>&gt; Should there be a design guideline rule for colons : in Swift?<br>&gt;<br>&gt; I see people doing things like this:<br>&gt;<br>&gt; protocol A : B {}<br>&gt;<br>&gt; // VS.<br>&gt;<br>&gt; protocol A: B {}<br>&gt; func foo&lt;T : A&gt;() -&gt; T { … }<br>&gt;<br>&gt; // VS.<br>&gt;<br>&gt; func foo&lt;T: A&gt;() -&gt; T { … }<br>&gt; var value : Type<br>&gt;<br>&gt; // VS.<br>&gt;<br>&gt; var value: Type<br>&gt; [key1 : value1, key2 : value2]<br>&gt;<br>&gt; // VS.<br>&gt;<br>&gt; [key1: value1, key2: value2]<br>&gt; I prefer the second style, where there is no whitespace between lhs<br>&gt; and the : symbol and there is also a whitespace after :. Example:<br>&gt; something: somethingElse<br></p><p>The standard library uses &quot; : &quot; for conformances and inheritance, and <br>&quot;: &quot; for type annotation.  FWIW.<br></p><p>-- <br>Dave<br></p></div></li></ul></div>    </main>
